        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"890057\">@ZhiKai Pong</span> What are the main difficult(ies) you have faced with the Fourier Transform?</p>",
        "id": 528049595,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1752143522
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What I want to do is essentially this:<br>\n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_signal\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_signal</a></p>\n<p>but part of the difficulty also comes from not knowing exactly what I need, give me some time and let me sketch it out</p>",
        "id": 528050662,
        "sender_full_name": "ZhiKai Pong",
        "timestamp": 1752143922
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah I think the first thing I need to know is the exact domain (of functions R -&gt; C) that the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_transform\">Hilbert transform</a> is defined on.</p>",
        "id": 528051105,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1752144082
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/D8U-flbmBVETPFbIpa0xrqXy/image.png\">image.png</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/MKICRnncG5gwdn2fLUx4nYtH/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/D8U-flbmBVETPFbIpa0xrqXy/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1213x400\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/D8U-flbmBVETPFbIpa0xrqXy/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/MKICRnncG5gwdn2fLUx4nYtH/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1230x833\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/MKICRnncG5gwdn2fLUx4nYtH/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>so the premise is this, given a \"signal\" <code>V ≥(t)</code> I want to construct a signal <code>V(t) = V ≥(t) + H(V ≥(t))</code> where <code>H</code> is the Hilbert transform. From the text I believe the Hilbert transform is just from a real function to another real function, and the \"signal\" <code>V ≥(t)</code> should be square integrable, but I don't know enough about functional anlysis to be certain of this or if there's anything else I'm missing.</p>\n<p>To complicate things further, under this framework I also want to represent a simple <code>cos(œâ*t)</code> with <code>Complex.exp (Complex.I*œâ*t)</code> (where <code>œâ = 2œÄŒΩ</code>). Just from the formula this seems to work if <code>a(ŒΩ)</code> is just the Dirac delta, and this makes me think <code>a(ŒΩ)</code> should be <code>SchwartzMap</code>. However I think <code>cos</code> isn't square integrable and I'm reading on how people work around this.</p>",
        "id": 528080300,
        "sender_full_name": "ZhiKai Pong",
        "timestamp": 1752153572
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My plan was to define  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ŒΩ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a(\\nu)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.06366em;\">ŒΩ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>œï</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ŒΩ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi(\\nu)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">œï</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.06366em;\">ŒΩ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> in a structure, and from that structure define (1), (2), (4), and prove (3) and (5) (as suggested <a href=\"#narrow/channel/479953-PhysLean/topic/Interest.20in.20Optics/near/522893578\">here</a>). as mentioned <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ŒΩ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a(\\nu)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.06366em;\">ŒΩ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> should be a distribution, so one can have dirac-delta functions etc.</p>\n<p>One could then also define a function which takes a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V(t)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to this structure and show that under certain conditions it is an inverse of (1), probably via Fourier transform api but again this is something I don't know how to at the moment.</p>",
        "id": 528080843,
        "sender_full_name": "ZhiKai Pong",
        "timestamp": 1752153735
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"890057\">ZhiKai Pong</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/479953-PhysLean/topic/Fourier.20Transform/near/528080300\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Hilbert transform is just from a real function to another real function</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>surely you need to be integrable?</p>",
