    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>To complicate things further, under this framework I also want to represent a simple¬†<code>cos(œâ*t)</code>¬†with¬†<code>Complex.exp (Complex.I*œâ*t)</code>¬†(where¬†<code>œâ = 2œÄŒΩ</code>). Just from the formula this seems to work if¬†<code>a(ŒΩ)</code>¬†is just the Dirac delta, and this makes me think¬†<code>a(ŒΩ)</code>¬†should be¬†<code>SchwartzMap</code>. However I think¬†<code>cos</code>¬†isn't square integrable and I'm reading on how people work around this</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The same thing happens in quantum mechanics, you have wave-functions like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>k</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e^{i k x}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">ik</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, which are not square integrable. What people do there, and I think what may be possible here, is to consider two different spaces of functions. </p>\n<ol>\n<li>The first space is <code>SchwartzMap</code> or something similar. </li>\n<li>The second space is the dual of <code>SchwartzMap</code>. </li>\n</ol>\n<p>then e.g. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>k</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">e^{i k x}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">ik</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, the dirac delta function, the cosine etc, all live in the second (more general and larger) space, whilst all the 'physical' functions actually live in the first space (smaller) space. </p>\n<p>Maybe something similar could be done here with  <code>SchwartzMap</code> maybe replaced  to something larger like smooth square-integrable functions. (I don't know if <code>smooth square-integrable functions</code> is a nice function space, e.g. whether it has a good topology etc).</p>",
        "id": 528114214,
        "sender_full_name": "Joseph Tooby-Smith",
        "timestamp": 1752162930
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think we can start with some concrete examples -  for example let's calculate the fourier transform of a single cosine, and see how that should look like</p>",
        "id": 528114482,
        "sender_full_name": "ZhiKai Pong",
