    },
    {
        "content": "<p>looking at <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Analysis/Distribution/FourierSchwartz.html#SchwartzMap.fourierTransformCLM\">SchwartzMap.fourierTransformCLM</a> is just very overwhelming and I have no idea what it's saying (what's a <code>BorelSpace</code>, what is V and E etc.)</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">noncomputable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">SchwartzMap</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">fourierTransformCLM</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">RCLike</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_2</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedAddCommGroup</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚ÑÇ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">SMulCommClass</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚ÑÇ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_3</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedAddCommGroup</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">InnerProductSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚Ñù</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">FiniteDimensional</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚Ñù</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">MeasurableSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">BorelSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"n\">SchwartzMap</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">‚Üí</span><span class=\"n\">L</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">SchwartzMap</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I kind of know the Fourier transform can be viewed as¬†a transformation between a function space and its dual space, but this statement had no significance to me whatsoever for performing calculations. I understand it is important and will take time to learn but at the same time this is what I mentioned about this being probably too abstract for an engineer/physicist and PhysLean should try to bridge this gap</p>",
        "id": 528116852,
        "sender_full_name": "ZhiKai Pong",
        "timestamp": 1752163723
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=BorelSpace#doc\">docs#BorelSpace</a> is a true-false statement, not a space. <code>BorelSpace V</code> means \"the measure space structure on V and the topology on V are compatible\"</p>",
        "id": 528122208,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1752165538
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"890057\">ZhiKai Pong</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/479953-PhysLean/topic/Fourier.20Transform/near/528116852\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>looking at <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Analysis/Distribution/FourierSchwartz.html#SchwartzMap.fourierTransformCLM\">SchwartzMap.fourierTransformCLM</a> is just very overwhelming and I have no idea what it's saying (what's a <code>BorelSpace</code>, what is V and E etc.)</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">noncomputable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">SchwartzMap</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">fourierTransformCLM</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">RCLike</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_2</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedAddCommGroup</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚ÑÇ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">SMulCommClass</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚ÑÇ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_3</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">NormedAddCommGroup</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">InnerProductSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚Ñù</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">FiniteDimensional</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">‚Ñù</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">MeasurableSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">BorelSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"n\">SchwartzMap</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">‚Üí</span><span class=\"n\">L</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">ùïú</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">SchwartzMap</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">V</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">E</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I kind of know the Fourier transform can be viewed as¬†a transformation between a function space and its dual space, but this statement had no significance to me whatsoever for performing calculations. I understand it is important and will take time to learn but at the same time this is what I mentioned about this being probably too abstract for an engineer/physicist and PhysLean should try to bridge this gap</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I agree with this, although I think it is in general going to be very difficult to do - but no one said any of this was meant to be easy :). </p>\n<p>I think one thing we can do to help (although does not solve the problem fully) is to pick a couple of files, maybe one for each area of physics, and make it an 'entry' point to the project or that area, by writing really careful and full documentation, maybe with examples. For example,  <a href=\"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean/blob/master/PhysLean/SpaceAndTime/Space/Basic.lean\">SpaceAndTime.Space.Basic</a> could be used, with better documentation and examples etc, as an entry point of the project. We could then collate these entry points into a list for people to reference. </p>\n<p>Obviously one could do something like this outside of the project (which is something I tried to do with <a href=\"https://notes.physlean.com\">https://notes.physlean.com</a>), but one quickly runs into dependency issues etc. when things are changed.</p>",
        "id": 528293888,
        "sender_full_name": "Joseph Tooby-Smith",
        "timestamp": 1752224426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://web.abo.fi/fak/mnf/mate/kurser/fourieranalys/chap3.pdf\">https://web.abo.fi/fak/mnf/mate/kurser/fourieranalys/chap3.pdf</a></p>\n<p>I don't know if I'm saying something redundant here, but here's a pdf talking about Fourier transform of distributions. Does this look helpful?</p>",
